#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:262
msgid "## Display and identification"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:264
msgid "### `clear` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:266
msgid ""
"The `clear` command clears the contents of the terminal screen. In fact, to "
"be more precise, it shifts the display so that the command prompt is at the "
"top of the screen on the first line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:268
msgid ""
"In a terminal, the display will be permanently hidden, whereas in a "
"graphical interface, a scrollbar will allow you to go back in the history of "
"the virtual terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:271
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! tip\n"
"    <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>L</kbd> will have the same effect as the `clear` command\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:273
msgid "### `echo` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:275
msgid "The `echo` command is used to display a string of characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:277
msgid ""
"This command is most commonly used in administration scripts to inform the "
"user during execution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:279
msgid ""
"The `-n` option will not return to the line after displaying the text (which "
"is the default behavior of the command)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:281
msgid ""
"For various reasons, the script developer may need to use special sequences "
"(starting with a `\\` character). In this case, the `-e` option will be "
"stipulated, allowing interpretation of the sequences."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:283
msgid "Among the frequently used sequences, we can mention :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:291
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Sequence | Result                |\n"
"| -------- | --------------------- |\n"
"| `\\a`     | Send a sonor bip      |\n"
"| `\\b`     | Back                  |\n"
"| `\\n`     | Adds a line break     |\n"
"| `\\t`     | Adds a horizontal tab |\n"
"| `\\v`     | Adds vertical tab     |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:293
msgid "### `date` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:295
msgid ""
"The `date` command displays the date and time. The command has the following "
"syntax:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:299
msgid "```bash date [-d AAAAMMJJ] [format] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:308
msgid ""
"```bash $ date Mon May 24 16:46:53 CEST 2021 $ date -d 20210517 +%j 137 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:310
msgid ""
"In this last example, the `-d` option displays a given date. The `+%j` "
"option formats this date to show only the day of the year."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:313
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Warning\n"
"    The format of a date can change depending on the value of the language defined in the environment variable `$LANG`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:315
msgid "The date display can follow the following formats:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:334
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                                             | Format                           |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------- |\n"
"| `+%A`                                                                                                              | Full Name of Day                 |\n"
"| `+%B`                                                                                                              | Full Name of Month               |\n"
"| `+%c`                                                                                                              | Full Date Display                |\n"
"| `+%d`                                                                                                              | Day number                       |\n"
"| `+%F`                                                                                                              | Date in `YYYY-MM-DD` format      |\n"
"| `+%G`                                                                                                              | Year                             |\n"
"| `+%H`                                                                                                              | Time of day                      |\n"
"| `+%j`                                                                                                              | Day of the year                  |\n"
"| `+%m`                                                                                                              | Month number                     |\n"
"| `+%M`                                                                                                              | Minute                           |\n"
"| `+%R`                                                                                                              | Time in `hh:mm` format           |\n"
"| `+%s`                                                                                                              | Seconds since January 1, 1970    |\n"
"| `+%T`                                                                                                              | Time in `hh:mm:ss` format        |\n"
"| `+%u`                                                                                                              | Day of the week (`1` for Monday) |\n"
"| `+%V`                                                                                                              | Week number (`+%V`)              |\n"
"| `+%x`                                                                                                              | Date in format `DD/MM/YYYY`      |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:336
msgid ""
"The `date` command also allows you to change the system date and time. In "
"this case, the `-s` option will be used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:340
msgid "```bash [root]# date -s \"2021-05-24 10:19\" ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:342
msgid "The format to be used following the `-s` option is this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:346
msgid "```bash date -s \"[AA]AA-MM-JJ hh:mm:[ss]\" ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:348
msgid "### `id`, `who` and `whoami` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:350
msgid ""
"The `id` command displays the name of the current user and its groups or "
"those of a user, if the user's login is given as an argument."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:355
msgid ""
"```bash $ id rockstar uid=1000(rockstar) gid=1000(rockstar) "
"groups=1000(rockstar),10(wheel)  ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:357
msgid ""
"The `-g`, `-G`, `-n` and `-u` options display the main group GID, subgroup "
"GIDs, names instead of numeric identifiers, and the user's UID respectively."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:359
msgid "The `whoami` command displays the login of the current user."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:361
msgid "The `who` command alone displays the names of logged in users:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:367
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```bash\n"
"$ who\n"
"rockstar tty1   2021-05-24 10:30\n"
"root     pts/0  2021-05-24 10:31\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:369
msgid ""
"Since Linux is multi-user, it is likely that multiple sessions are open on "
"the same station, either physically or over the network. It is interesting "
"to know which users are logged in, if only to communicate with them by "
"sending messages."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:372
msgid "tty: represents a terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:372
msgid ""
"pts/: represents a virtual console in a graphical environment with the "
"number after representing the instance of the virtual console (0, 1, 2...)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:374
msgid ""
"The `-r` option also displays the execution level (see chapter \"startup\")."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:376
msgid "## File tree"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:378
msgid ""
"In Linux, the file tree is an inverted tree, called a **single hierarchical "
"tree**, whose root is the directory `/`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:380
msgid "The **current directory** is the directory where the user is located."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:382
msgid ""
"The **connection directory** is the working directory associated with the "
"user. The login directories are, by default, stored in the `/home` directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:384
msgid "When the user logs in, the current directory is the login directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:386
msgid ""
"An **absolute path** references a file from the root by traversing the "
"entire tree to the file level:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:388
msgid "`/home/groupA/alice/file`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:390
msgid ""
"The **relative path** references that same file by traversing the entire "
"tree from the current directory:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:392
msgid "`../alice/file`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:394
msgid ""
"In the above example, the \"`..`\" refers to the parent directory of the "
"current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:396
msgid ""
"A directory, even if it is empty, will necessarily contain at least **two "
"references** :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:399
msgid "`.`: reference to itself."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:399
msgid "`..`: reference to the parent directory of the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:401
msgid ""
"A relative path can thus start with `./` or `../`. When the relative path "
"refers to a subdirectory or file in the current directory, then the `./` is "
"often omitted. Mentioning the first `./` in the tree will only really be "
"required to run an executable file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:403
msgid ""
"Errors in paths can cause many problems: creating folders or files in the "
"wrong places, unintentional deletions, etc. It is therefore strongly "
"recommended to use auto-completion when entering paths."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:405
msgid "![our example tree](images/commands-pathabsolute.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:407
msgid ""
"In the above example, we are looking to give the location of the file "
"`myfile` from the directory of bob."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:410
msgid ""
"By an **absolute path**, the current directory does not matter. We start at "
"the root, and work our way down to the directories `home`, `groupA`, `alice` "
"and finally the file `myfile`: `/home/groupA/alice/myfile`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:410
msgid ""
"By a **relative path**, our starting point being the current directory "
"`bob`, we go up one level through `..` (i.e., into the `groupA` directory), "
"then down into the alice directory, and finally the `myfile` file: `../alice/"
"myfile`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:412
msgid "### `pwd` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:414
msgid ""
"The `pwd` (Print Working Directory) command displays the absolute path of "
"the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:419
msgid "```bash $ pwd /home/rockstar ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:421
msgid ""
"To move around using a relative path, you must know its position in the tree."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:423
msgid ""
"Depending on the command interpreter, the command prompt may also display "
"the name of the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:425
msgid "### `cd` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:427
msgid ""
"The `cd` (Change Directory) command allows you to change the current "
"directory, in other words, to move through the tree."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:439
msgid ""
"```bash $ cd /tmp $ pwd /tmp $ cd ../ $ pwd / $ cd $ pwd /home/rockstar ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:441
msgid ""
"As you can see in the last example above, the command `cd` with no arguments "
"moves the current directory to the `home directory`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:443
msgid "### `ls` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:445
msgid "The `ls` command displays the contents of a directory"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:449
msgid "```bash ls [-a] [-i] [-l] [directory1] [directory2] [â¦] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:456
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```bash\n"
"$ ls /home\n"
".    ..    rockstar\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:458
msgid "The main options of the `ls` command are :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:464
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                       | Information                                                                                                                          |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n"
"| `-a`                                                         | Displays all files, even hidden ones. Hidden files in Linux are those beginning with `.`.                                            |\n"
"| `-i`                                                         | Displays inode numbers.                                                                                                              |\n"
"| `-l`                                                         | The `-l` command displays a vertical list of files with additional information formatted in columns.                                 |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:466
msgid "The `ls` command, however, has a lot of options (see `man`):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:477
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                       | Information                                                                                                                          |\n"
"| ------                                                       | ------------                                                                                                                         |\n"
"| `-d`                                                         | Displays information about a directory instead of listing its contents.                                                              |\n"
"| `-g`                                                         | Displays UID and GID rather than owner names.                                                                                        |\n"
"| `-h`                                                         | Displays file sizes in the most appropriate format (byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, ...). `h` stands for Human Readable.         |\n"
"| `-s`                                                         | Displays the size in bytes (unless `k` option).                                                                                      |\n"
"| `-A`                                                         | Displays all files in the directory except `.` and `.`.                                                                              |\n"
"| `-R`                                                         | Displays the contents of subdirectories recursively.                                                                                 |\n"
"| `-F`                                                         | Displays the type of files. Prints a `/` for a directory, `*` for executables, `@` for a symbolic link, and nothing for a text file. |\n"
"| `-X`                                                         | Sort files according to their extensions.                                                                                            |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:479
msgid "Description of columns:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:484
msgid ""
"```bash $ ls -lia /home 78489 drwx------ 4 rockstar rockstar 4096 25 oct. "
"08:10 rockstar ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:495
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Value           | Information                                                                                                   |\n"
"| --------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `78489`         | Inode Number.                                                                                                 |\n"
"| `drwx------`    | File type (`d`) and rights (`rwx------`).                                                                       |\n"
"| `4`             | Number of subdirectories (`.` and `..` included). For a file of type physical link: number of physical links. |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | For a physical link file: number of physical links.                                                           |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | For a file of type physical link: number of physical links.                                                   |\n"
"| `4096`          | For a physical link type file: number of physical links.                                                      |\n"
"| `25 oct. 08:10` | Last modified date.                                                                                           |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | The name of the file (or directory).                                                                          |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:498
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    **Aliases** are frequently positioned in common distributions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:500
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This is the case of the alias `ll`:\n"
