#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:585
msgid "```bash $ ls /etc --hide=*.conf ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:587
msgid "### `mkdir` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:589
msgid "The `mkdir` command creates a directory or directory tree."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:593
msgid "```bash mkdir [-p] directory [directory] [...] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:599
msgid "```bash $ mkdir /home/rockstar/work ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:602
msgid ""
"The \"rockstar\" directory must exist to create the \"work\" directory.  "
"Otherwise, the `-p` option should be used. The `-p` option creates the "
"parent directories if they do not exist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:605
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Danger\n"
"    It is not recommended to use Linux command names as directory or file names.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:607
msgid "### `touch` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:609
msgid ""
"The `touch` command changes the timestamp of a file or creates an empty file "
"if the file does not exist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:613
msgid "```bash touch [-t date] file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:615
msgid "Example :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:619
msgid "```bash $ touch /home/rockstar/myfile ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:623
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                            | Information                                                                |\n"
"| --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-t date`                         | Changes the date of last modification of the file with the specified date. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:625
msgid "Date format: `[AAAA]MMJJhhmm[ss]`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:628
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Tip\n"
"    The `touch` command is primarily used to create an empty file, but it can be useful for incremental or differential backups for example. Indeed, the only effect of executing a `touch` on a file will be to force it to be saved during the next backup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:630
msgid "### `rmdir` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:632
msgid "The `rmdir` command deletes an empty directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:638
msgid "```bash $ rmdir /home/rockstar/work ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:642
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                  | Information |\n"
"| ----------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------- |\n"
"| `-p` |  Removes the parent directory or directories provided if they are empty.           |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:645
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Tip\n"
"    To delete both a non-empty directory and its contents, use the `rm` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:647
msgid "### `rm` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:649
msgid "The `rm` command deletes a file or directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:653
msgid "```bash rm [-f] [-r] file [file] [...] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:656
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Danger\n"
"    Any deletion of a file or directory is final.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:662
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Information                              |\n"
"| ------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-f`    | Do not ask for confirmation of deletion. |\n"
"| `-i`    | Requires confirmation of deletion.       |\n"
"| `-r`    | Recursively deletes subdirectories.      |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:665
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    The `rm` command itself does not ask for confirmation when deleting files. However, with a RedHat/Rocky distribution, `rm` does ask for confirmation of deletion because the `rm` command is an `alias` of the `rm -i` command. Don't be surprised if on another distribution, like Debian for example, you don't get a confirmation request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:667
msgid ""
"Deleting a folder with the `rm` command, whether the folder is empty or not, "
"will require the `-r` option to be added."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:669
msgid "The end of the options is signaled to the shell by a double dash `--`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:671
msgid "In the example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:678
msgid ""
"```bash $ >-hard-hard # To create an empty file called -hard-hard hard-hard "
"[CTRL+C] To interrupt the creation of the file $ rm -f -- -hard-hard ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:680
msgid ""
"The hard-hard file name starts with a `-`. Without the use of the `--` the "
"shell would have interpreted the `-d` in `-hard-hard` as an option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:682
msgid "### `mv` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:684
msgid "The `mv` command moves and renames a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:688
msgid "```bash mv file [file ...] destination ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:695
msgid ""
"```bash $ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 $ mv /home/rockstar/"
"file1 /home/rockstar/file2 /tmp ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:700
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options                                                                        | Information                                                     |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-f`                                                                           | Don't ask for confirmation if overwriting the destination file. |\n"
"| `-i`                                                                           | Request confirmation if overwriting destination file (default). |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:702
msgid ""
"A few concrete cases will help you understand the difficulties that can "
"arise:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:706
msgid "```bash $ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:708
msgid ""
"Renames `file1` to `file2`, if `file2` already exists, it will be replaced "
"by `file1`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:712
msgid "```bash $ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 /tmp ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:714
msgid "Moves `file1` and `file2` into the `/tmp` directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:718
msgid "```bash $ mv file1 /repexist/file2 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:720
msgid "Moves `file1` into `repexist` and renames it `file2`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:724
msgid "```bash $ mv file1 file2 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:726
msgid "`file1` is renamed to `file2`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:730
msgid "```bash $ mv file1 /repexist ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:732
msgid "If the destination directory exists, `file1` is moved to `/repexist`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:736
msgid "```bash $ mv file1 /wrongrep ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:738
msgid ""
"If the destination directory does not exist, `file1` is renamed to "
"`wrongrep` in the root directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:740
msgid "### `cp` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:742
msgid "The `cp` command copies a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:746
msgid "```bash cp file [file ...] destination ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:752
msgid "```bash $ cp -r /home/rockstar /tmp ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:759
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Information                                                      |\n"
"| ------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-i`    | Request confirmation if overwriting (default).                   |\n"
"| `-f`    | Do not ask for confirmation if overwriting the destination file. |\n"
"| `-p`    | Keeps the owner, permissions and timestamp of the copied file.   |\n"
"| `-r`    | Copies a directory with its files and subdirectories.            |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:763
msgid "```bash cp file1 /repexist/file2 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:765
msgid "`file1` is copied to `/repexist` under the name `file2`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:769
msgid "```bash $ cp file1 file2 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:771
msgid "`file1` is copied as `file2` to this directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:775
msgid "```bash $ cp file1 /repexist ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:777
msgid "If the destination directory exists, `file1` is copied to `/repexist`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:781
msgid "```bash $ cp file1 /wrongrep ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:783
msgid ""
"If the destination directory does not exist, `file1` is copied under the "
"name `wrongrep` to the root directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:785
msgid "## Visualization"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:787
msgid "### `file` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:789
msgid "The `file` command displays the type of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:793
msgid "```bash file file1 [files] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:801
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```bash\n"
"$ file /etc/passwd /etc\n"
"/etc/passwd:    ASCII text\n"
"/etc:        directory\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:803
msgid "### `more` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:805
msgid ""
"The `more` command displays the contents of one or more files screen by "
"screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:809
msgid "```bash more file1 [files] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:817
msgid "```bash $ more /etc/passwd root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash ...  ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:819
msgid ""
"Using the <kbd>ENTER</kbd> key, the move is line by line. Using the "
"<kbd>SPACE</kbd> key, the move is page by page. `/text` allows you to search "
"for the occurrence in the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:821
msgid "### `less` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:823
msgid ""
"The `less` command displays the contents of one or more files. The `less` "
"command is interactive and has its own commands for use."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:827
msgid "```bash less file1 [files] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:829
msgid "The commands specific to `less` are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:840
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Command           | Action                                          |\n"
"| ----------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `h`               | Help.                                           |\n"
"| `Arrows`          | Move up, down a line, or to the right or left.. |\n"
"| `Enter`           | Move down one line.                             |\n"
"| `Space`           | Move down one page.                             |\n"
"| `PgUp` and `PgDn` | Move up or down one page.                       |\n"
"| `Begin` and `End` | Move to the beginning or end of a file.         |\n"
"| `/texte`          | Search for text.                                |\n"
"| `q`               | Quit the `less` command.                        |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:842
msgid "### `cat` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:844
msgid ""
"The `cat` command concatenates the contents of multiple files and displays "
"the result on the standard output."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:848
msgid "```bash cat file1 [files] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:850
msgid "Example 1 - Displaying the contents of a file to the standard output :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:854
msgid "```bash $ cat /etc/passwd ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:856
msgid ""
"Example 2 - Displaying the contents of multiple files to standard output:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:860
msgid "```bash $ cat /etc/passwd /etc/group ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:862
msgid ""
"Example 3 - Displaying the contents of several files in the file "
"`usersAndGroups.txt` :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:866
msgid "```bash $ cat /etc/passwd /etc/group > usersAndGroups.txt ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:868
msgid "Example 4 - Displaying the line numbering :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:879
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```bash\n"
"$ cat -n /etc/profile\n"
"     1    # /etc/profile: system-wide .profile file for the Bourne shell (sh(1))\n"
"     2    # and Bourne compatible shells (bash(1), ksh(1), ash(1), ...).\n"
"     3\n"
"     4    if [ \"`id -u`\" -eq 0 ]; then\n"
"     5      PATH=\"/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin\"\n"
"     6    else\n"
"â¦\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:881
msgid "Example 5 - Shows the numbering of non-empty lines:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:886
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```bash\n"
"$ cat -b /etc/profile\n"
"     1    # /etc/profile: system-wide .profile file for the Bourne shell (sh(1))\n"
"     2    # and Bourne compatible shells (bash(1), ksh(1), ash(1), ...).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:892
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"     3    if [ \"`id -u`\" -eq 0 ]; then\n"
"     4      PATH=\"/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin\"\n"
"     5    else\n"
"â¦\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:894
msgid "### `tac` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:896
msgid ""
"The `tac` command does almost the opposite of the `cat` command. It displays "
"the contents of a file starting from the end (which is particularly "
"interesting for reading logs!)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:898
msgid "Example: Display a log file by displaying the last line first:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:902
msgid "```bash [root]# tac /var/log/messages | less ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:904
msgid "### `head` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:906
msgid "The `head` command displays the beginning of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:910
msgid "```bash head [-n x] file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:914
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                                | Observation                             |\n"
"| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-n x`                                                                                                | Display the first `x` lines of the file |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:916
msgid ""
"By default (without the `-n` option), the `head` command will display the "
"first 10 lines of the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:918
msgid "### `tail` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:920
msgid "The `tail` command displays the end of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:924
msgid "```bash tail [-f] [-n x] file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:929
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option   | Observation                               |\n"
"| -------- | ----------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-n x`   | Displays the last `x` lines of the file   |\n"
"| `-f`     | Displays changes to the file in real time |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:938
msgid ""
"```bash tail -n 3 /etc/passwd sshd:x:74:74:Privilege-separeted sshd:/var/"
"empty /sshd:/sbin/nologin tcpdump::x:72:72::/:/sbin/nologin user1:x:500:500:"
"grp1:/home/user1:/bin/bash ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:940
msgid ""
"With the `-f` option, the `tail` command does not give back and runs until "
"the user interrupts it with the sequence <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd>. "
"This option is very frequently used to track log files (the logs) in real "
"time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:942
msgid ""
"Without the `-n` option, the tail command displays the last 10 lines of the "
"file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:944
msgid "### `sort` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:946
msgid "The `sort` command sorts the lines of a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:948
msgid ""
"It allows you to order the result of a command or the content of a file in a "
"given order, numerically, alphabetically, by size (KB, MB, GB) or in reverse "
"order."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:952
msgid "```bash sort [-kx] [-n] [-o file] [-ty] file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:960
msgid ""
"```bash $ sort -k3 -t: -n /etc/passwd root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash adm:"
"x:3:4:adm:/var/adm/:/sbin/nologin ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:968
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                                                                                                                                                               | Observation                                  |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-kx`                                                                                                                                                                                                                                | Specifies the `x` column to sort on          |\n"
"| `-n`                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 | Requests a numeric sort                      |\n"
"| `-o file   `                                                                                                                                                                                                                         | Saves the sort to the specified file         |\n"
"| `-ty`                                                                                                                                                                                                                                | Specifies the field separator character `y`. |\n"
"| `-r`                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 | Reverse the order of the result              |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:970
msgid ""
"The `sort` command sorts the file only on the screen. The file is not "
"modified by the sorting. To save the sort, use the `-o` option or an output "
"redirection `>`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:972
msgid ""
"By default, the numbers are sorted according to their character. Thus, "
"\"110\" will be before \"20\", which will itself be before \"3\". The `-n` "
"option must be specified so that the numeric character blocks are sorted by "
"their value."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:974
msgid ""
"The `sort` command reverses the order of the results, with the `-r` option:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:980
msgid ""
"```bash $ sort -k3 -t: -n -r /etc/passwd root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash adm:"
"x:3:4:adm:/var/adm/:/sbin/nologin ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:982
msgid ""
"In this example, the `sort` command will sort the contents of the `/etc/"
"passwd` file this time from largest uid to smallest."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:984
msgid "Some advanced examples of using the `sort` command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:986
msgid "Shuffling values"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:988
msgid ""
"The `sort` command also allows you to shuffle values with the `-R` option:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:992
msgid "```bash $ sort -R /etc/passwd ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:994
msgid "Sorting IP addresses"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:996
msgid ""
"A system administrator is quickly confronted with the processing of IP "
"addresses from the logs of his services such as SMTP, VSFTP or Apache. These "
"addresses are typically extracted with the `cut` command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:998
msgid "Here is an example with the file `dns-client.txt` :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1006
msgid ""
"``` 192.168.1.10 192.168.1.200 5.1.150.146 208.128.150.98 208.128.150.99 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1015
msgid ""
"```bash $ sort -nr dns-client.txt 208.128.150.99 208.128.150.98 "
"192.168.1.200 192.168.1.10 5.1.150.146 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1017
msgid "Sorting file by sizes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1019
msgid ""
"The `sort` command knows how to recognize file sizes, from commands like "
"`ls` with the `-h` option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1021
msgid "Here is an example with the file `size.txt` :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1034
msgid "``` 1,7G 18M 69K 2,4M 1,2M 4,2G 6M 124M 12,4M 4G ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1048
msgid ""
"```bash $ sort -hr size.txt 4,2G 4G 1,7G 124M 18M 12,4M 6M 2,4M 1,2M 69K ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1050
msgid "### `wc` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1052
msgid ""
"The `wc` command counts the number of lines, words and/or bytes in a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1056
msgid "```bash wc [-l] [-m] [-w] file [files] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1063
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option | Observation                     |\n"
"| ------ | ------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-c`   | Count the number of bytes.      |\n"
"| `-m`   | Count the number of characters. |\n"
"| `-l`   | Counts the number of lines.     |\n"
"| `-w`   | Counts the number of words.     |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1065
msgid "## Search"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1067
msgid "### `find` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1069
msgid "The `find` command searches for files or directories location."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1073
msgid ""
"```bash find directory [-name name] [-type type] [-user login] [-date date] "
"```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1075
msgid ""
"Since there are so many options to the `find` command, it is best to refer "
"to the `man`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1077
msgid ""
"If the search directory is not specified, the `find` command will search "
"from the current directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1082
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option              | Observation                            |\n"
"| ------------------- | -------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-perm permissions` | Search for files by their permissions. |\n"
"| `-size size`        | Search for files by size.              |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1084
msgid "### `-exec` option of the `find` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1086
msgid ""
"It is possible to use the `-exec` option of the `find` command to execute a "
"command on each result line:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1090
msgid "```bash $ find /tmp -name *.txt -exec rm -f {} \\; ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1092
msgid ""
"The previous command searches for all files in the `/tmp` directory named `*."
"txt` and deletes them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1095
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Tip \"Understand the `-exec` option\"\n"
"    In the example above, the `find` command will construct a string representing the command to be executed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1097
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If the `find` command finds three files named `log1.txt`, `log2.txt`, and `log3.txt`, then the `find` command will construct the string by replacing in the string `rm -f {} \\;` the braces with one of the results of the search, and do this as many times as there are results.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1099
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This will give us :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1103
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    rm -f /tmp/log1.txt ; rm -f /tmp/log2.txt ; rm -f /tmp/log3.txt ;\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1105
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `;` character is a special shell character that must be protected by a `\\` to prevent it from being interpreted too early by the `find` command (and not in the `-exec`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1108
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Tip\n"
"    `$ find /tmp -name *.txt -delete` does the same thing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1110
msgid "### `whereis` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1112
msgid "The `whereis` command searches for files related to a command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1116
msgid "```bash whereis [-b] [-m] [-s] command ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1123
msgid "```bash $ whereis -b ls ls: /bin/ls ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option | Observation                     |\n"
"| ------ | ------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-b`   | Search only the binary file.    |\n"
"| `-m`   | Searches only for man pages.    |\n"
"| `-s`   | Searches only for source files. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1131
msgid "### `grep` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1133
msgid "The `grep` command searches for a string in a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1137
msgid "```bash grep [-w] [-i] [-v] \"string\" file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1144
msgid ""
"```bash $ grep -w \"root:\" /etc/passwd root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                  | Observation                             |\n"
"| --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-i`                                                                                    | Ignore the case of the searched string. |\n"
"| `-v`                                                                                    | Excludes lines containing the string.   |\n"
"| `-w`                                                                                    | Search for the exact word.              |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1154
msgid ""
"The `grep` command returns the complete line containing the string you are "
"looking for.  * The `^` special character is used to search for a string at "
"the beginning of a line.  * The special character `$` searches for a string "
"at the end of a line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1158
msgid "```bash $ grep -w \"^root\" /etc/passwd ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1161
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    This command is very powerful and it is highly recommended to consult its manual. It has many derivatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1163
msgid ""
"It is possible to search for a string in a file tree with the `-R` option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1167
msgid "```bash grep -R \"Virtual\" /etc/httpd ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1169
msgid "### Meta-characters (wildcards)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1171
msgid ""
"Meta-characters replace one or more characters (or even an absence of "
"characters) during a search. These meta-characters are also known as "
"wildcards. They can be combined. The `*` character replaces a string "
"composed of any characters. The `*` character can also represent an absence "
"of character."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1180
msgid ""
"```bash $ find /home -name \"test*\" /home/rockstar/test /home/rockstar/"
"test1 /home/rockstar/test11 /home/rockstar/tests /home/rockstar/test362 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1182
msgid ""
"Meta-characters allow more complex searches by replacing all or part of a "
"word. Simply replace the unknowns with these special characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1184
msgid "The character `?` replaces a single character, whatever it is."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1190
msgid ""
"```bash $ find /home -name \"test?\" /home/rockstar/test1 /home/rockstar/"
"tests ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1192
msgid ""
"The square brackets `[` are used to specify the values that a single "
"character can take."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1199
msgid ""
"```bash $ find /home -name \"test[123]*\" /home/rockstar/test1 /home/"
"rockstar/test11 /home/rockstar/test362 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1202
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    Always surround words containing meta-characters with `\"` to prevent them from being replaced by the names of files that meet the criteria.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Warning\n"
"    Do not confuse shell meta-characters with regular expression meta-characters. The `grep` command uses regular expression meta-characters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1207
msgid "## Redirects and pipes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1209
msgid "### Standard input and output"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1211
msgid ""
"On UNIX and Linux systems, there are three standard streams. They allow "
"programs, via the `stdio.h` library, to input or output information."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1213
msgid "These streams are called X channel or X file descriptor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1217
msgid ""
"By default: * the keyboard is the input device for channel 0, called "
"**stdin** ; * the screen is the output device for channels 1 and 2, called "
"**stdout** and **stderr**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1219
msgid "![standards channels](images/input-output.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1221
#, no-wrap
msgid "**stderr** receives the error streams returned by a command. The other streams are directed to **stdout**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1223
msgid ""
"These streams point to peripheral files, but since everything is a file in "
"UNIX/Linux, I/O streams can easily be diverted to other files. This "
"principle is the strength of the shell."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1225
msgid "### Input redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1227
msgid ""
"It is possible to redirect the input stream from another file with the "
"character `<` or `<<`. The command will read the file instead of the "
"keyboard:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1231
msgid "```bash $ ftp -in serverftp << ftp-commands.txt ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1234
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    Only commands that require keyboard input will be able to handle input redirection.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1236
msgid ""
"Input redirection can also be used to simulate user interactivity. The "
"command will read the input stream until it encounters the defined keyword "
"after the input redirection."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1238
msgid "This feature is used to script interactive commands:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1246
msgid ""
"```bash $ ftp -in serverftp << END user alice password put file bye END ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1248
msgid "The keyword `END` can be replaced by any word."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1256
msgid ""
"```bash $ ftp -in serverftp << STOP user alice password put file bye STOP ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1258
msgid ""
"The shell exits the `ftp` command when it receives a line containing only "
"the keyword."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1261
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Warning\n"
"    The ending keyword, here `END` or `STOP`, must be the only word on the line and must be at the beginning of the line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1263
msgid ""
"The standard input redirection is rarely used because most commands accept a "
"filename as an argument."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1265
msgid "The command `wc` could be used like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1272
msgid ""
"```bash $ wc -l .bash_profile 27 .bash_profile # the number of lines is "
"followed by the file name $ wc -l < .bash_profile 27 # returns only the "
"number of lines ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1274
msgid "### Output redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1276
msgid ""
"Standard output can be redirected to other files using the `>` or `>>` "
"characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1278
msgid "The simple `>` redirection overwrites the contents of the output file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1282
msgid "```bash $ date +%F > date_file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1284
msgid ""
"while the double redirection `>>` adds (concatenates) to the content of the "
"output file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1288
msgid "```bash $ date +%F >> date_file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1290
msgid ""
"In both cases, the file is automatically created when it does not exist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1292
msgid ""
"The standard error output can also be redirected to another file. This time "
"it will be necessary to specify the channel number (which can be omitted for "
"channels 0 and 1):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1297
msgid "```bash $ ls -R / 2> errors_file $ ls -R / 2>> errors_file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1299
msgid "### Examples of redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1301
msgid "Redirection of 2 outputs to 2 files :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1305
msgid "```bash $ ls -R / >> ok_file 2>> nok_file ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1307
msgid "Redirection of the 2 outputs to a single file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1311
msgid "```bash $ ls -R / >> log_file 2>&1 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1313
msgid "Redirection of *stderr* to a \"bottomless pit\" (`/dev/null`) :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1317
msgid "```bash $ ls -R / 2>> /dev/null ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1319
msgid ""
"When both output streams are redirected, no information is displayed on the "
"screen. To use both the output redirection and to keep the display, you will "
"have to use the command `tee`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1321
msgid "### Pipes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1323
msgid ""
"A **pipe** is a mechanism allowing you to link the standard output of a "
"first command to the standard input of a second command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1325
msgid ""
"This communication is uni directional and is done with the `|` symbol. The "
"pipe symbol `|` is obtained by pressing the <kbd>SHIFT</kbd> + <kbd>|</kbd> "
"simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1327
msgid "![pipe](images/pipe.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1329
msgid ""
"All data sent by the control on the left of the pipe through the standard "
"output channel is sent to the standard input channel of the control on the "
"right."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1331
msgid "The commands particularly used after a pipe are filters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1335
msgid "Display only the beginning:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1339
msgid "```bash $ ls -lia / | head ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1341
msgid "Display only the end:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1345
msgid "```bash $ ls -lia / | tail ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1347
msgid "Sort the result:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1351
msgid "```bash $ ls -lia / | sort ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1353
msgid "Count the number of words / characters:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1357
msgid "```bash $ ls -lia / | wc ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1359
msgid "Search for a string in the result:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1363
msgid "```bash $ ls -lia / | grep fichier ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1365
msgid "## Special points"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1367
msgid "### `tee` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1369
msgid ""
"The `tee` command is used to redirect the standard output of a command to a "
"file while maintaining the screen display."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1371
msgid ""
"It is combined with the `|` pipe to receive as input the output of the "
"command to be redirected:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1376
msgid "```bash $ ls -lia / | tee fic $ cat fic ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1378
msgid "The `-a` option adds to the file instead of overwriting it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1380
msgid "### `alias` and `unalias` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1382
msgid ""
"Using **alias** is a way to ask the shell to remember a particular command "
"with its options and give it a name."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1384
#: docs/books/admin_guide/06-users.md:498
#: docs/books/learning_ansible/02-advanced.md:69
#: docs/books/learning_ansible/03-working-with-files.md:108
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1388
msgid "```bash $ ll ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1390
msgid "will replace the command :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1394
msgid "```bash $ ls -l ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1396
msgid ""
"The `alias` command lists the aliases for the current session. Aliases are "
"set by default on Linux distributions. Here, the aliases for a Rocky server :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1405
msgid ""
"```bash $ alias alias l.='ls -d .* --color=auto' alias ll='ls -l --"
"color=auto' alias ls='ls --color=auto' alias vi='vim' alias which='alias | /"
"usr/bin/which --tty-only --read-alias --show-dot --show-tilde' ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1407
msgid ""
"The aliases are only defined temporarily, for the time of the user session."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1409
msgid "For permanent use, they must be created in the :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1412
msgid "`.bashrc` file in the user's login directory;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1412
msgid "`/etc/profile.d/alias.sh` file for all users."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1415
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Warning\n"
"    Special care must be taken when using aliases which can be potentially dangerous! For example, an alias set up without the administrator's knowledge :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1419
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```bash\n"
"    alias cd='rm -Rf'\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1421
msgid "The `unalias` command allows you to delete aliases."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1423
msgid "To delete a single alias:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1427
msgid "```bash $ unalias ll ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1429
msgid "To delete all aliases:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
